<br>
The problem with space exploration has always been justifying its cost to the rest of society.  Most people do not have the same imperative that we scientists, engineers and explorers do.  We will need to have a damned good reason for going before the government will cough up the dough.  It would require even more justification if we want to do it via a commercial effort.  The vague (though not insignificant) possibilities of planet wide disasters are a hard sell, and I hate to use fear as our selling tool (though it has always been the most effective one).  I think that we will see a lot of abortive starts in this direction (like SEI in the late eighties), but the necessary long term commitment to space may only come when the popular set of priorities and philosophies change, and that is a hard thing to predict.  Other than science fiction, what can we do to advance this agenda?<br>
<br>
The problem with nuclear space propulsion in particular (as an essential component of space exploration) is that it is likely to be VERY expensive.  Add the percieved risks, and you have an even greater sales challenge.  It seems to me that we first have to convince people that manned space exploration and commercialization is important enough (with the attendent problems above).  If you can pull that off, then we may have the resources to address the real technical and safety problems.<br>
<br>
I DO believe that we need to remove the risk of contamination to the biosphere by radioactive materials.  That means either developing engines that run on something relatively safe (hydrogen, etc.), or finding a non-terrestrial source of the required fissionable materials (or both).  Does anyone have a perspective on the likelihood of the later (uranium mines on asteroids?)?  Unfortunately, even TESTING a nuclear rocket on the Earth is a highly charged issue.  I remember a few years ago when the aerospace industry's Joint Propulsion Conference was wall to wall nuclear propulsion papers.  Ultimately, one of the things that sunk the program at NASA was the cost of building a completely contained altitude test stand.  My thoughts are that we will ultimately need a rocket test facility on the Moon.  Until we can answer these risks, I don't think it will EVER happen, even with strong popular support for space exploration in general.<br>
<br>
So, I hope I haven't rehashed too much that everyone has already agreed to as given groundrules.  I would be really interested in hearing what you all think of these matters, especially in the context of recently proposed programs like Prometheus. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/7/03 5:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=765.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Devlopment barriers for nuclear space propulsion</span><hr size=1> <br>
