imately wants to save money it should support nuclear power in space.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3278<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/7/03 11:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=765.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Devlopment barriers for nuclear space propulsion</span><hr size=1> I agree with our need to address public fears but not the cost issue. That isn't likely to come up as a major obstacle. Nuclear is simply the only practical option. Trying to achieve anything meaningful in space requires it. If people are prepared to pay for a mars mission for example, they will dish out the roughly 50 billion dollars or so in taxes to achieve it. Without nuclear power it would be a much harder sell. Certainly a lot more expensive. Dismissing old nuclear myths and explaining risk mitigation methods are ways to win over public support. We can't leave them in the dark or they will look for information from unreliable sources such as anti-nuclear groups. The key to nuclear spaceflight is an informed public and one which wants to see bold new endeavours in space. I'm currently trying to write articles which both educate and instill a sense of adventure.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=reactorboy>reactorboy</A></span><br