<br>
Incidentally, I do feel that discovery of life on other planets MIGHT change the funding and public support landscape significantly.  I don't think that more pictures of Io and Europa, or even Pluto will be much of an incentive, but LIFE might just be the key, especially if it is more than single celled organisms. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 360<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/21/03 3:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=765.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What happened to SEI, then?</span><hr size=1> Nuclear is actually cheaper.  SEI was doomed by Battlestar Galactica visions, not nuclear power!<br>
<br>
You can do much more with a nuclear thermal propulsion based mission to mars than with a chemical one-verstaility is a factor.  So you don't judge based on the one application- you base its economical value on the value of everything it replaces.  For example, it replaces:<br>
<br>
1) Chemical fuels<br>
2) Chemical boosters<br>
3) In flight and surface power plant<br>
4) Can crack its own fuel<br>
5) Can power a hybrid NEP (ion) stage, for higher isp<br>
6) <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Much</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> more payload for an equivalent mass, or scaled down mass for equivalent payload.<br>
<br>
There are a number of other applications, but these are a few.  Certainly, nuclear propulsion pays for itself. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NS Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 959<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/21/03 4:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=765.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What happened to SEI, then?</span><hr size=1> I agree with Zen on this one.  Even though, as with everything else, the initial R&amp;D for developing the nuclear technologies will be costly, the compactness and simplicity that nuclear power provides to space missions will make it pay for itself over the long run.  If we want to send people to Mars I just don't see any alternatives that would be safer, cheaper, and less massive than to use nuclear reactors.  There's an excellent article by Robert Zubrin on this site's homepage defending the use of nuclear power in space.  If you haven't read it I'd highly recommend checking it out.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showPrevMessage?topicID=765.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showNextMessage?topicID=765.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=765.topic&i